      "comment_id" : 113124767,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "The post was moved here: <a href=\"https://ruediste.github.io/java/kryo/2017/05/07/serializing-non-serializable-lambdas.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">ruediste.github.io/java/kryo/2017/05/07/&hellip;</a>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1350880,
      "reputation" : 3069,
      "user_id" : 1290557,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 60,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/H05hO.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "ruediste",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1290557/ruediste"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1602493534,
    "last_edit_date" : 1602493534,
    "creation_date" : 1494158374,
    "answer_id" : 43831210,
    "question_id" : 22807912,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you are willing to switch to another serialization framework like <a href=\"https://github.com/EsotericSoftware/kryo\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Kryo</a>, you can get rid of the multiple bounds or the requirement that the implemented interface must implement <code>Serializable</code>. The approach is to</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Modify the <code>InnerClassLambdaMetafactory</code> to always generate the code required for serialization</li>\n<li>Directly call the <code>LambdaMetaFactory</code> during deserialization</li>\n</ol>\n<p>For details and code see this <a href=\"https://ruediste.github.io/java/kryo/2017/05/07/serializing-non-serializable-lambdas.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">blog post</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 4494144,
        "reputation" : 318,
        "user_id" : 3654441,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/eJSUc.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "slevin",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3654441/slevin"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 4,
      "creation_date" : 1509568965,
      "post_id" : 45699173,
      "comment_id" : 81074822,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "I like this answer because then any external caller you don&#39;t write will automatically also be serializable. If you want objects submitted to be serializable, your interface should be serializable, which is kind of the point of an interface. However, the question did say &quot;without creating a <code>SerializableRunnable</code> &#39;dummy&#39; interface&quot;"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4126293,
      "reputation" : 415,
      "user_id" : 3767904,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cbdcd0f6df4fe0d2b56a634de1b47bb7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Pascal",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3767904/pascal"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 30,
    "last_activity_date" : 1502821674,
    "creation_date" : 1502821674,
    "answer_id" : 45699173,
    "question_id" : 22807912,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Very ugly cast. I prefer to define a Serializable extension to the functional interface I'm using</p>\n\n<p>For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>interface SerializableFunction&lt;T,R&gt; extends Function&lt;T,R&gt;, Serializable {}\ninterface SerializableConsumer&lt;T&gt; extends Consumer&lt;T&gt;, Serializable {}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>then the method accepting the lambda can be defined as such :</p>\n\n<pre><code>private void someFunction(SerializableFunction&lt;String, Object&gt; function) {\n   ...\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>and calling the function you can pass your lambda without any ugly cast:</p>\n\n<pre><code>someFunction(arg -&gt; doXYZ(arg));\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 16216212,
      "reputation" : 1017,
      "user_id" : 11708983,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-9nCKNJVKnMA/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAABrw/XaFMGillkzM/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
